			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>Automated Selective Caching for Reference Attribute Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EmmaSöderberg.html">Emma Söderberg</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_2">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_2</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagM">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> The core contribution is a profiling-based selective caching strategy that improves compiler time/memory performance.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The work is grounded in reference attribute grammars as a meta-language for specifying language semantics and generating tools.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> It reports an experimental evaluation on a generated Java compiler using benchmark/test suites.
</li></ul></li></ul>
